   <text type="translation">
      <body>
         <pb facs="1865_10_09_Kniffler_Yokohama_von_Gildemeister_Ries_Bremen_1.tif" n="envelope"/>
         <p>Via Marseille<lb/>BREMEN TH. &amp; TX. <lb/>9/10<lb/>1N-6N GILDEMEISTER &amp;
                RIES<lb/>BREMEN<lb/>Messrs. L. Kniffler + Co.<lb/>TOUR
                T<lb/>11<lb/>OCT.<lb/>65<lb/>FORBACH<lb/>P.P.<lb/>P.P. paid Yokohama<lb/>⟨1865
                Gildemeister + Ries<lb/>Bremen 9th Oct.<lb/>a[nswered]/ Dec 16th<lb/>Decb. 30⟩</p>
         <pb facs="1865_10_09_Kniffler_Yokohama_von_Gildemeister_Ries_Bremen_2.tif" n="2"/>
         <p>Bremen October 9th 1865<lb/>
            <lb/>Messrs. L. Kniffler + Co.<lb/>Yokohama<lb/>With reference to our respectful
                <lb/>letter from 9th Sep[?], today we would just <lb/>like to pass on to you a bill
                of lading for <lb/>cigars transported to you by Messrs. <lb/>Aschenheim + Fuhrken in
                London by<lb/>steamer. These cigars<lb/>are for your Mr. Hermann<lb/> Gildemeister,
                for whom we pass <lb/>you the enclosed insert and we ask<lb/>you to credit us for
                the amount of<lb/>⟨Mem fol. 47⟩Goldre[?] 313.56 gt ⅌ 3rd<lb/>March 1866.<lb/>In the
                business it has been getting <lb/>more lively everywhere recently. <lb/>Especially
                cotton has significantly gone<lb/>up in price. The quick rise of the <lb/>discounts
                in London to<lb/>7%, however, has calmed the <lb/>goods market again for the
                <lb/>moment. <lb/>We send you our best greetings, <lb/>Yours sincerely <lb/>p.p.
                Gildemeister+Ries<lb/>H. Schmidt<lb/>Postage paid<lb/>With<lb/>insert</p>
         <pb facs="1865_10_09_Kniffler_Yokohama_von_Gildemeister_Ries_Bremen_3.tif" n="3"/>
         <pb facs="1865_10_09_Kniffler_Yokohama_von_Gildemeister_Ries_Bremen_4.tif" n="4"/>
      </body>
